    "We say that a map h: E → ℓ 2, where E ⊂ R n, is finitely L-biLipschitz, if there exists some n 0, such that for all n ≥ n 0, the mapP n • h is L-biLipschitz.Note that by basic properties of projections, any finitely L-biLipschitz map is also L-biLipschitz.In the following, ∥•∥ stands for both the Euclidean norm on R d and the norm induced by the canonical scalar product on ℓ 2.",
    "Which norm is in use is given by the argument.",
    "Figure 2 illustrates the following lemma.",
    "Let d ∈ N, L ≥ 1, ε > 0.",
